Consider the following.

```python
@ray.actor
class Foo(object):
  pass

actors = [Foo() for _ in range(1000)]  
```

Every time a `Foo` object is created, the `Foo` class will be pickled and exported to all of the workers. Since every newly created actor also processes every export, this is an N^2 algorithm.

This is likely responsible for some Redis congestion that we've been seeing.

@pcmoritz is currently working on this.

```Modelica
model InputAlias
    input Real x;
    Real alias;
equation
    der(x) = alias;
end InputAlias;
```
This fails on the alias detection, because the state "der(x)" does not exist in any of the variable lists. If one disables alias detection it does not fail, but the relationship between `x` and its derivative is lost.
